scribes to an ironic sense of hope all the while issuing an appeal for a largely unaccomplished nationhood, simultaneously insisting on a linguistic solidarity. In a folkloric literature that has an overarching theory of poetics – perhaps even trans-figurative cognitive poetics due to the multi-faceted nature of its application and the complexity of its linguistic structure – the relationship of man (and less frequently woman) with others takes center stage in many of the folkloric creations. Arts are not figurative representations of the real in the Kurdish world; they are the real.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aArts, Kurdish. 0aEpic poetry, Kurdish. 0aFables, Kurdish. 0aFolk dancing, Kurdish. 0aFolk literature, Kurdish. 0aFolk songs, Kurdish. 0aKurdish literature. 4aCultural sociology. 4aFolklore. 4aKurds. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aKurds, folklore.  acultural sociology.1 aBajalan, Djene R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaran, Suat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarwari, Zuzan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChyet, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDehqan, Mustafa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEccarius-Kelly, Vera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoff, Leonard Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorangy, Alireza, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKreyenbroek, Philip G.1 aKreyenbroek, Philip G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharifi, Amir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWerner, Eberhard, econtributor.4ctb4https: